---
/**
 * Keep inline tags on one line with outer spaces (Astro whitespace).
 * Never break before <em>/<strong>/<a> after a word: newline alone is stripped → "theEssay".
 */
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="John Locke: Consciousness Continuity as Proto-Trajectory | Foundations | Identity Engineering">
	<main class="min-h-screen">
		<section class="border-b border-white/10 px-6 pt-28 pb-16">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
				<a href="/foundations" class="mb-6 inline-block text-sm text-white/40 transition hover:text-white/70">
					← Foundations
				</a>
				<div class="text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Foundations · John Locke</div>
				<h1 class="mt-3 text-5xl font-bold tracking-tighter leading-[0.95] text-white md:text-6xl">
					Consciousness Continuity as Proto-Trajectory
				</h1>
				<p class="mt-6 max-w-2xl text-xl font-light leading-relaxed text-white/50">
					The forensic root of personal identity, and the earliest sketch of what Identity Engineering calls the Identity Stem.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="px-6 py-16">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl space-y-12 text-lg leading-relaxed text-white/55">
				<div>
					<div class="mb-3 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">1 · Empiricism</div>
					<p>
						Locke is the classical British empiricist. In the <a href="https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/An_Essay_Concerning_Human_Understanding" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-white/75 underline decoration-white/25 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white hover:decoration-white/50"><em class="not-italic">Essay Concerning Human Understanding</em></a> (1689) he argues against the rationalists who postulated innate ideas.
					</p>
					<ul class="mt-4 list-disc space-y-2 pl-5 text-white/55">
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Tabula rasa:</strong> the mind at birth is a blank slate. All ideas come from experience.
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Two sources of ideas:</strong> sensation (external world) and reflection (internal operations: thinking, doubting, willing, perceiving).
						</li>
					</ul>
					<p class="mt-4">
						Philosophy here is “research in the mind”: conceptual analysis and thought experiments. Identity Engineering is related in spirit: conceptual modeling with geometric primitives, inspired by empirical physics, still building toward operational and empirical tests.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div>
					<div class="mb-3 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">2 · Personal identity</div>
					<p>
						Locke sharply distinguishes between <strong class="text-white/80">Man</strong> (biological organism, bodily continuity) and <strong class="text-white/80">Person</strong> (thinking, intelligent being with reason and reflection that can consider itself as itself).
					</p>
					<p class="mt-4">
						Personal identity consists solely in the <strong class="text-white/80">continuity of consciousness</strong> (sameness of consciousness) over time, primarily mediated by memory: the ability to extend consciousness backward to past actions and thoughts. See <a href="https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/An_Essay_Concerning_Human_Understanding/Book_II/Chapter_XXVII" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-white/70 underline decoration-white/25 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white hover:decoration-white/50">Book II, Chapter 27 (“Of Identity and Diversity”)</a>.
					</p>
					<p class="mt-4">
						The Prince and the Cobbler thought experiment: the consciousness of a prince enters the body of a cobbler. The <em class="text-white/75 not-italic">Person</em> remains the prince, accountable for princely deeds, even though the <em class="text-white/75 not-italic">Man</em> is now the cobbler. Identity tracks consciousness, not substance (body or soul).
					</p>
					<p class="mt-4">
						Person is a <em class="text-white/75 not-italic">forensic term</em>: it concerns accountability, responsibility, reward and punishment.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div>
					<div class="mb-3 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">3 · Relevance for Identity Engineering</div>
					<ul class="space-y-4">
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Sameness-as-trajectory:</strong> Locke supplies the historical root. Identity is not static substance but continuity of consciousness across time: a proto-trajectory. The framework extends this with an active component (Vision Gradient as prospective opening of future freedom) and geometric dynamics (Stem as stable axis around which continuity can rotate and curve).
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">State differential:</strong> corresponds to the backward extension of consciousness (memory as coherence maintenance).
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Identity Stem:</strong> the inner core from which conscious continuity derives stability (in Locke, implicitly the “same self” that reflects).
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Forensic dimension:</strong> fits the Architect level and Dual Mission (responsibility also in substrate-free contexts).
						</li>
					</ul>
					<p class="mt-6">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Differentiation:</strong> Locke is retrospective and memory-based. Identity Engineering is prospective and active: Vision Gradient plus conscious design of the geometry. Locke shows that identity is “designable” in the sense of accountability; the framework makes design explicit and physics-informed.
					</p>
					<p class="mt-4">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Empirie gap:</strong> Locke’s theory is pure thought experiment. That is precisely where the framework begins: from philosophical analysis toward engineering-supported, potentially testable practice (Questions as Probes, operationalization via psychological process models). See also <a href="/critical-gaps" class="text-white/70 underline decoration-white/25 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white hover:decoration-white/50">Critical Gaps</a>.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="border-t border-white/10 bg-white/[0.015] px-6 py-16">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl space-y-8 text-lg leading-relaxed text-white/55">
				<div>
					<div class="mb-2 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Sources</div>
					<ul class="space-y-2 text-base text-white/50">
						<li>
							Primary: John Locke, <a href="https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/An_Essay_Concerning_Human_Understanding" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-white/70 underline decoration-white/25 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white hover:decoration-white/50"><em class="not-italic">An Essay Concerning Human Understanding</em></a> (1689), esp. <a href="https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/An_Essay_Concerning_Human_Understanding/Book_II/Chapter_XXVII" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-white/70 underline decoration-white/25 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white hover:decoration-white/50">Book II, Ch. 27</a>.
						</li>
						<li>
							Overview: <a href="https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/locke-personal-identity/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-white/70 underline decoration-white/25 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white hover:decoration-white/50">Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy: Locke on Personal Identity</a>.
						</li>
					</ul>
				</div>
				<div>
					<div class="mb-2 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Related</div>
					<p>
						This anchor is developed in the essay <a href="/blog/identity-engineering-vs-classical-identity-theories" class="text-white/80 underline decoration-white/25 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white hover:decoration-white/50">Identity Engineering vs. Classical Identity Theories</a>. Next planned anchor: Parfit <em class="text-white/70 not-italic">(Reasons and Persons)</em>, successor and critic of Locke in the psychological continuity debate.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="border-t border-white/10 px-6 py-14">
			<div class="mx-auto flex max-w-3xl flex-col gap-4 text-sm sm:flex-row sm:items-center sm:justify-between">
				<a href="/foundations" class="text-white/50 transition hover:text-white/80">← All foundations</a>
				<div class="flex flex-wrap gap-x-6 gap-y-2">
					<a href="/ontology" class="text-white/50 underline decoration-white/20 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white/80 hover:decoration-white/40">Ontology</a>
					<a href="/blog" class="text-white/50 underline decoration-white/20 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white/80 hover:decoration-white/40">Blog</a>
					<a href="/framework" class="text-white/50 underline decoration-white/20 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white/80 hover:decoration-white/40">Framework</a>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>
	</main>
</Layout>
